WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.050
Daniel Holmgren: Hey, everybody

00:00:08.080 --> 00:00:08.960
.

00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:10.000
My name is Daniel Holmgren.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.270
I'm the head of protocol at Blue Sky.

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:15.000
Just a heads up, I've been losing my voice all

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:15.310
week.

00:00:15.310 --> 00:00:18.040
I thought maybe if I drank six Modellos at the

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:20.800
after party last night, that would loosen it up.

00:00:20.800 --> 00:00:22.520
And the jury's out on if that's working or not

00:00:22.520 --> 00:00:22.700
.

00:00:22.710 --> 00:00:27.380
So I'm hoping that I'm good for this talk.

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:29.590
To tell you a little bit about, so I lead protocol

00:00:29.720 --> 00:00:31.730
development and design at Blue Sky.

00:00:31.730 --> 00:00:34.110
To tell you a little bit about our team, right now

00:00:34.250 --> 00:00:36.360
it's technically just me and Brian Newbold on it,

00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:39.420
although we collaborate closely with other folks from the Atmosphere

00:00:39.420 --> 00:00:39.750
team.

00:00:39.750 --> 00:00:42.400
Without going into our whole org structure, the reason that we

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:46.700
split out this protocol department is that protocol design and governance just

00:00:46.700 --> 00:00:49.420
looks pretty different from running a startup.

00:00:49.420 --> 00:00:52.580
You want to make slower intentional decisions and you don't want

00:00:52.580 --> 00:00:55.380
it to get caught up in sort of the market and the

00:00:55.380 --> 00:00:58.120
product life cycle of the startup.

00:00:58.120 --> 00:01:00.590
So we put up a little bit of a internal firewall for

00:01:00.590 --> 00:01:03.280
that department so we can go a little bit slower and we

00:01:03.280 --> 00:01:06.040
can be focused on what we really care about with the protocol

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:09.040
, which is the emergence of a functioning, resilient, multi

00:01:09.070 --> 00:01:10.300
-stakeholder atmosphere.

00:01:10.300 --> 00:01:16.230
So I want to start with the provocation, which is

00:01:16.230 --> 00:01:19.070
that it's logically impossible for Blue Sky to decentralize the

00:01:19.070 --> 00:01:19.540
network.

00:01:19.540 --> 00:01:22.290
We really want the network to be decentralized.

00:01:22.300 --> 00:01:25.740
It is impossible for us to do it because we are the

00:01:25.740 --> 00:01:26.860
party, right?

00:01:26.860 --> 00:01:29.230
And even if we funded somebody else to do it, they

00:01:29.230 --> 00:01:31.230
're still downstream of us and it's not actually, do

00:01:31.240 --> 00:01:32.270
they actually have the authority?

00:01:32.270 --> 00:01:33.300
Do they actually have the power?

00:01:33.300 --> 00:01:36.960
We're the central entity.

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:38.860
We can't decentralize it.

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:42.630
We can provide the tools and structures by which to decentralize

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:45.590
it, but we need others to use those tools and structures

00:01:45.590 --> 00:01:48.910
to take control, power, and authority in the network to

00:01:49.190 --> 00:01:51.700
actually make this a resilient multi-stakeholder network.

00:01:51.700 --> 00:01:55.590
So that's what I'm going to be talking about today

00:01:55.590 --> 00:01:57.580
is those tools and structures and how we address that.

00:01:57.580 --> 00:01:59.560
The agenda is pretty brief.

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:01.860
We're going to talk about the IETF, some

00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:06.100
recent developments with PLC governance, and then hard decentralization

00:02:06.100 --> 00:02:08.670
, which is kind of getting into the actual threats of what

00:02:08.910 --> 00:02:11.930
having a big entity in the middle of the ecosystem could do

00:02:11.930 --> 00:02:12.160
.

00:02:12.370 --> 00:02:15.760
Before we do that, I'm on the big stage and

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:18.090
I wanted to talk about the real governance question, which is

00:02:18.090 --> 00:02:20.880
how do we capitalize and stylize AT protocol?

00:02:20.880 --> 00:02:23.440
Again, this is a multi-stakeholder network,

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:24.660
so this is just my opinion.

00:02:24.660 --> 00:02:26.160
It just happens to be the correct opinion.

00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:30.870
You can see AT protocol, at proto, all lowercase

00:02:30.870 --> 00:02:33.010
, not a capital A, and atmosphere.

00:02:33.010 --> 00:02:36.480
The rest of these are out, especially capital A, capital

00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:38.740
T, capital P, proto.

00:02:38.890 --> 00:02:41.300
That one is terrible, and it needs to be killed.

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:45.190
Okay, now onto the real stuff.

00:02:45.190 --> 00:02:48.660
Talking about the IETF, or who gets to decide

00:02:48.660 --> 00:02:50.720
what the protocol actually is.

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:52.510
So, what is the IETF?

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:54.640
It's the Internet Engineering Task Force.

00:02:54.660 --> 00:02:57.200
It's the standards body for the Internet.

00:02:57.200 --> 00:02:59.860
It standardized all the protocols that you know and love.

00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:01.330
I'm sure that you're familiar with a lot of these

00:03:01.330 --> 00:03:01.350
.

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:01.520
SMTP for email, HTTP for the web, TLS

00:03:01.530 --> 00:03:01.800
, it gives you the little green lock that tells you that

00:03:01.820 --> 00:03:02.040
your website's secure, web sockets, OAuth,

00:03:02.040 --> 00:03:02.280
and more.

00:03:02.300 --> 00:03:10.300
To tell you a little bit

00:03:10.300 --> 00:03:15.200
about the vibe of the IETF, it's a

00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:18.030
pretty weird, idiosyncratic organization.

00:03:18.030 --> 00:03:20.300
I have a quote here from Snarf that I think captures

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:20.300
it pretty well.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:20.300
He said, standards bodies or bureaucracy for good, which I

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:20.300
think sums it up.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:20.300
It's pretty bureaucratic, it's pretty pedantic,

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:20.300
but it's ultimately a very idealistic organization.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:22.840
And it's a very neutral, credible body, and they

00:03:22.840 --> 00:03:25.190
do a very good job sort of stewarding and owning

00:03:25.190 --> 00:03:27.040
these sorts of Internet protocols.

00:03:27.310 --> 00:03:35.280
So, it's a mix of institutional, but it's

00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:39.060
also grassroots.

00:03:39.060 --> 00:03:45.340
You kind of have like a lot of old Internet heads there

00:03:45.350 --> 00:03:48.100
, you have activists, you have academics and researchers, you

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:51.150
also have folks from the big tech companies that are Google and

00:03:51.150 --> 00:03:53.280
Cloudflare and others.

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:56.420
And that also gives it this mix of idealism and prag

00:03:56.450 --> 00:03:56.840
matism.

00:03:56.840 --> 00:04:00.530
People have conversations about keeping the Internet decentralized, but also they

00:04:00.530 --> 00:04:02.280
care a lot about the Internet working well.

00:04:02.280 --> 00:04:05.280
And so they have this very pragmatic approach.

00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:09.700
The kind of motto there is that decisions are made by rough

00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:13.280
consensus and working code, which I think actually gives a good

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:15.280
sense of that idealism and pragmatism.

00:04:15.280 --> 00:04:17.570
They want to see something working and they want to get a

00:04:17.590 --> 00:04:20.880
bunch of diverse voices in the room and have general agreement on

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:21.240
it.

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:22.280
It's open membership.

00:04:22.290 --> 00:04:24.280
Anybody can join.

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:25.730
You don't need to pay money to join.

00:04:25.870 --> 00:04:28.250
You can just hop in the mailing list, start participating.

00:04:28.250 --> 00:04:30.420
You can show up to meetings and start participating.

00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:32.660
And companies are not members of it.

00:04:32.660 --> 00:04:33.280
Individuals are members.

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:36.710
And I put kind of here because most people have an affili

00:04:36.710 --> 00:04:39.240
ation with a company and it's like they kind of where

00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:42.280
it's pretty clear that they are affiliated with companies.

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:45.670
But it is still it kind of gets at their ethos

00:04:45.670 --> 00:04:48.880
in a way, which is that these are these are engineers

00:04:48.880 --> 00:04:51.280
coming together trying to reach consensus on protocols.

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:57.560
So the exciting news is we have a working group at the

00:04:57.750 --> 00:04:58.280
IETF.

00:04:58.280 --> 00:05:03.270
Also huge kudos to Brian on that.

00:05:03.290 --> 00:05:05.280
Brian really let up the standards work.

00:05:05.290 --> 00:05:07.710
In all honesty, he should be the one up here presenting

00:05:07.710 --> 00:05:08.280
all of this.

00:05:08.280 --> 00:05:10.280
He's just done an incredible job at that.

00:05:10.280 --> 00:05:14.270
The working group is called Authenticated Transfer or ATP.

00:05:14.270 --> 00:05:18.280
This is the URL for it.

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:20.280
The responsible area director is Andy Newton.

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:24.630
The working group chairs are Shu Ping Peng and Mallory N

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:25.280
odell.

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:27.570
Brian and I got the chance to chat with all three of

00:05:27.590 --> 00:05:29.270
these folks earlier this week.

00:05:29.270 --> 00:05:31.260
Generally got very good vibes from them.

00:05:31.290 --> 00:05:33.280
They're ready to hit the ground running.

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:36.280
They're kind of like start engaging on the mailing list,

00:05:36.280 --> 00:05:37.280
draft up some stuff.

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:39.990
We want to have a lot of energy at the first meeting

00:05:39.990 --> 00:05:40.280
.

00:05:40.280 --> 00:05:42.270
So the vibes were good.

00:05:42.280 --> 00:05:43.270
I'm excited about this.

00:05:43.280 --> 00:05:46.280
This is our charter in very small font.

00:05:46.280 --> 00:05:49.380
You can read the entire thing on the IETF data

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:50.020
tracker.

00:05:50.280 --> 00:05:53.280
This was on the note of bureaucracy for good.

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:56.530
This was four months of going back and forth on a mailing

00:05:56.750 --> 00:05:59.850
list to get that nailed down to decide what we were going

00:05:59.850 --> 00:06:00.280
to work on.

00:06:00.280 --> 00:06:03.320
And to break down kind of what's in that, what

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:06.930
the charter for this working group is for is the structure of

00:06:06.930 --> 00:06:09.420
the repo and how we encode records in it, the

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:14.240
sync protocol for public repositories, the AT URI scheme

00:06:14.300 --> 00:06:18.380
for addressing records in those repositories, and then interface requirements

00:06:18.380 --> 00:06:21.280
and selection criteria for an identifier resolution system.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:24.050
This was kind of the hardest part of nailing down the

00:06:24.050 --> 00:06:26.540
charter, which is that we did not want to pull d

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:28.020
ids into the IETF.

00:06:28.290 --> 00:06:30.790
We did not want to wade into the quagm

00:06:30.800 --> 00:06:32.280
ire of specifying identity.

00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:35.320
So we kind of, there's an identity-shaped hole

00:06:35.330 --> 00:06:38.310
in the spec, and we're specifying the shape of

00:06:38.310 --> 00:06:39.020
that hole.

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:42.360
We are not going to be, this working group is not

00:06:42.360 --> 00:06:46.030
going to be doing lexicon, any microblogging

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:48.280
, or social semantics at all.

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:50.570
Identity, as I mentioned, labeling, and the permission

00:06:50.590 --> 00:06:52.890
data work that we're working on right now is outside of

00:06:52.890 --> 00:06:54.240
the working group as well.

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:56.950
Though, parts of this may, we may recharter

00:06:56.960 --> 00:07:00.380
the work, if everything goes well for both parties, we

00:07:00.400 --> 00:07:03.320
may recharter the working group in the future and address

00:07:03.320 --> 00:07:04.280
some of these.

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:06.730
So, just to call it out, this is your chance

00:07:06.730 --> 00:07:10.240
to contribute to the technical direction of the protocol.

00:07:10.280 --> 00:07:12.690
As I said, this is open membership, anybody can hop

00:07:12.690 --> 00:07:13.280
in here.

00:07:13.280 --> 00:07:15.070
If you think that we screwed it up and the protocol is

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:17.170
stupid or ugly or whatever, this is your chance to say

00:07:17.170 --> 00:07:20.020
it and actually have an impact on the protocol.

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:23.590
You, in some very real sense, you are on an

00:07:23.590 --> 00:07:27.720
equal playing field as Brian or I on that mailing list and

00:07:27.910 --> 00:07:29.280
in that room.

00:07:29.280 --> 00:07:31.540
So, just to give you a sense for participation, as

00:07:31.560 --> 00:07:33.270
I said, anyone can participate.

00:07:33.280 --> 00:07:35.440
There's three in-person meetings a year, one in

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:37.980
North America, one in Europe, and one in Asia generally

00:07:37.980 --> 00:07:38.270
.

00:07:38.280 --> 00:07:41.860
They have a very good remote-first experience, and usually

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:44.540
if you're attending remote and only for one day, they

00:07:44.750 --> 00:07:46.280
'll give you a free ticket.

00:07:46.280 --> 00:07:49.280
So, that is great.

00:07:49.280 --> 00:07:53.170
The first working group meeting will probably be at IETF

00:07:53.170 --> 00:07:57.280
126 in Vienna, which is this summer, July.

00:07:57.280 --> 00:08:01.120
We may do a remote interim meeting beforehand, and I will

00:08:01.120 --> 00:08:03.240
keep people updated on that.

00:08:03.280 --> 00:08:05.100
But regardless, follow along on the mailing list.

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:06.080
It's atp@ietf.

00:08:06.080 --> 00:08:06.280
org.

00:08:06.280 --> 00:08:08.570
Brian and I are going to be trying to send out some

00:08:08.570 --> 00:08:10.280
stuff on there somewhat soon.

00:08:10.280 --> 00:08:12.100
So, hop in and let us know your thoughts.

00:08:12.280 --> 00:08:14.070
Okay, on to the next one.

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:17.390
PLC, or what about that centralized server at the bottom

00:08:17.390 --> 00:08:18.250
of the stack?

00:08:18.280 --> 00:08:21.850
For those that don't know, PLC is the identifier

00:08:21.850 --> 00:08:26.280
, not identity, the identifier system for the AT protocol.

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:28.820
It's where your keys are stored, or yeah, it

00:08:28.820 --> 00:08:32.240
describes your public keys and your service endpoints.

00:08:32.280 --> 00:08:35.730
And it's kind of the centralized server run by Blue Sky

00:08:35.730 --> 00:08:38.240
right now at the bottom of the stack.

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:40.070
My odd take is PLC isn't that bad.

00:08:40.280 --> 00:08:42.100
The threat model is actually pretty limited.

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:45.280
Everything is cryptographically signed.

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:49.200
The threat model of whoever is running the PLC directory,

00:08:49.220 --> 00:08:51.270
what they can get away with, is not that much.

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:54.080
They can't arbitrarily change your identity or anything like that

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:54.280
.

00:08:54.280 --> 00:08:58.560
They can essentially do denial of service attacks, removing operations from

00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:01.280
your identity, or refusing to serve your identity.

00:09:01.280 --> 00:09:04.800
Those aren't good, but just to note the threat model

00:09:04.800 --> 00:09:06.270
is pretty limited.

00:09:06.280 --> 00:09:08.100
All that being said, it still needs some work.

00:09:08.280 --> 00:09:12.690
And so we're sort of thinking about maturing governance of

00:09:12.690 --> 00:09:14.240
PLC as we go along.

00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:16.520
We'd like to use DNS and ICANN as an

00:09:16.520 --> 00:09:21.020
example, mostly for an analogy of iterative maturation of

00:09:21.020 --> 00:09:22.280
governance.

00:09:22.280 --> 00:09:24.730
DNS has issues, ICANN has issues, don't

00:09:24.730 --> 00:09:27.740
overthink the analogy, but you can kind of see how

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:29.020
DNS evolved over time.

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:32.370
It started as a text file that got distributed to different hosts

00:09:32.370 --> 00:09:36.280
in the network, moved to a single server that was a

00:09:36.290 --> 00:09:39.100
computer under the desk, transitioned to multiple root servers.

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:42.280
ICANN got set up as a governance body for it

00:09:42.280 --> 00:09:45.280
, and ICANN continues to evolve in their governance,

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:47.860
being more and more multi-stakeholder, taking into

00:09:47.860 --> 00:09:49.990
account other countries outside of the U.

00:09:49.990 --> 00:09:50.270
S.

00:09:50.340 --> 00:09:51.240
more.

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:54.440
And so this is sort of the model that we look at

00:09:54.440 --> 00:09:56.200
with PLC is, you know, like we don't

00:09:56.200 --> 00:09:58.400
have to get it to the end state of like, this

00:09:58.460 --> 00:10:00.280
is the perfect PLC forever or something tomorrow.

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:04.280
It's how can we iteratively move that forward as the

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:06.280
like kind of threat model for the atmosphere evolves.

00:10:06.280 --> 00:10:10.830
So the exciting news to announce is that public ledger of

00:10:10.830 --> 00:10:14.280
credentials organization has officially been founded as a Swiss association.

00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:22.280
Again,

00:10:22.280 --> 00:10:25.690
huge kudos to Brian for leading this up as well as

00:10:25.690 --> 00:10:27.980
Matt, our head of legal, which if you guys can

00:10:27.980 --> 00:10:28.400
find, I don't know if Matt's here, but

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:30.090
if you guys can find Matt, you should talk to Matt

00:10:30.090 --> 00:10:30.100
.

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:31.940
He's like protocol-pilled now, it's very

00:10:31.940 --> 00:10:32.100
fun.

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:36.630
So we put a lot of thought into who is going to

00:10:36.630 --> 00:10:39.020
be on the board for PLC.

00:10:39.280 --> 00:10:43.790
Like we wanted a board that people in the ecosystem could really

