You should come talk to him.

00:11:54.280 --> 00:11:55.580
And then Tyla, and I don't know how to

00:11:55.870 --> 00:11:57.890
pronounce her last name, unfortunately, but she's a crypt

00:11:57.890 --> 00:12:01.280
ographer and a security and privacy engineer at Google.

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:07.240
She also lives in Switzerland, which is quite nice for organizational

00:12:07.260 --> 00:12:08.020
reasons.

00:12:08.280 --> 00:12:11.520
Yeah, so just to note again, this is like the

00:12:11.520 --> 00:12:14.240
first step in the evolution of PLC.

00:12:14.280 --> 00:12:15.280
This isn't the end state of it.

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:17.100
We're going to continue working on this.

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:20.060
We also haven't actually transferred any assets over to PLC

00:12:20.060 --> 00:12:20.280
.

00:12:20.280 --> 00:12:23.110
That is something that we'll be doing in the coming months

00:12:23.110 --> 00:12:24.280
, and we'll give updates as that happens.

00:12:24.280 --> 00:12:29.610
The first order of business is getting the domain name over to

00:12:29.610 --> 00:12:30.240
PLC.

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:33.870
Alongside these organizational improvements, we also have some technical improvements

00:12:33.870 --> 00:12:34.200
to PLC.

00:12:34.280 --> 00:12:39.130
We ship streaming replication and a replica reference implementation that provides full

00:12:39.130 --> 00:12:41.280
verification of all directory operations.

00:12:41.280 --> 00:12:43.400
There's a number of people that are running this in the

00:12:43.400 --> 00:12:44.280
network already.

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:46.670
And the longer-term plan is a sophistication of that

00:12:46.670 --> 00:12:48.250
, which is transparency logs.

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:51.370
And you know that we're going to do that because we

00:12:51.370 --> 00:12:53.270
have Filippo on the board.

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:56.280
Great.

00:12:56.280 --> 00:12:59.430
Now, so those are sort of like the governance updates on

00:12:59.430 --> 00:13:02.240
like kind of these core parts of the protocol.

00:13:02.280 --> 00:13:05.590
This next section is about hard decentralization, or that's

00:13:05.590 --> 00:13:07.880
great and all, but what happens when blue sky kills API

00:13:07.880 --> 00:13:08.270
access?

00:13:08.280 --> 00:13:11.870
Or servers are actually just physical objects that can be destroyed,

00:13:11.870 --> 00:13:13.270
unplugged, or seized.

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:15.350
This is kind of the real politic of running a multi-

00:13:15.350 --> 00:13:18.540
stakeholder network where you have one big person at the

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:19.270
center of it.

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:21.850
What are the particular threats, and what can they get away

00:13:21.850 --> 00:13:22.280
with?

00:13:22.280 --> 00:13:25.290
So, I want to call out that decentralization isn't

00:13:25.290 --> 00:13:27.440
just one thing, and we need to think through what those

00:13:27.450 --> 00:13:28.270
threats actually are.

00:13:28.280 --> 00:13:31.730
Numbers are important, but I'm somewhat uninterested in

00:13:31.730 --> 00:13:35.020
like what percentage of people are on what thing or what.

00:13:35.280 --> 00:13:38.180
It's what are the actual threats that come from blue sky

00:13:38.180 --> 00:13:40.270
being outsized in this ecosystem.

00:13:40.280 --> 00:13:43.150
Let's think through those threats, and think through how blue

00:13:43.150 --> 00:13:46.020
sky can address them, and how the network can address them

00:13:46.080 --> 00:13:46.260
.

00:13:46.280 --> 00:13:49.090
So, we're going to do some threat modeling on what

00:13:49.090 --> 00:13:51.120
blue sky could do, and then we're going to talk

00:13:51.130 --> 00:13:52.260
through some of the solutions.

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:55.190
So, the most common thing that people think of is blue

00:13:55.190 --> 00:13:57.270
sky shuts down AppView API access.

00:13:57.280 --> 00:14:00.150
People are familiar with this because a lot of social companies in

00:14:00.150 --> 00:14:01.250
the past have done it.

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:03.740
This is actually sort of the threat that I'm least concerned

00:14:03.790 --> 00:14:07.420
about, because data access is guaranteed by the open hosting PD

00:14:07.460 --> 00:14:08.020
S layer.

00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:11.500
As long as the hosting layer, the network inherits its

00:14:11.500 --> 00:14:14.340
openness from the PDS layer, and as long as the

00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:18.570
hosting layer remains locked open, then these other AppView implement

00:14:18.590 --> 00:14:21.270
ations can emerge as the need arises.

00:14:21.280 --> 00:14:23.740
I've somewhat jokingly in the past called this lazy decentral

00:14:23.790 --> 00:14:26.960
ization, that it's if you trust that the hosting layer

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:29.350
is open, then you don't need to decentralize the

00:14:29.350 --> 00:14:30.280
app layer yet.

00:14:30.280 --> 00:14:32.490
But you have to trust that the hosting layer is open,

00:14:32.490 --> 00:14:34.270
and we'll talk about that in a second.

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:36.800
Still, the things that we need for this are tools for

00:14:36.800 --> 00:14:39.270
backfilling the network, and syncing the network,

00:14:39.300 --> 00:14:42.280
and also AppView implementation code.

00:14:44.280 --> 00:14:46.740
So, now to talk about if we screwed up the hosting

00:14:46.770 --> 00:14:50.020
layer, this would be blue sky shutting down access to the

00:14:50.020 --> 00:14:52.480
PDS, or access to the open data that's hosted

00:14:52.480 --> 00:14:53.280
by the PDS.

00:14:53.280 --> 00:14:55.750
To note, blue sky, if blue sky were to do

00:14:55.750 --> 00:14:58.790
this, it destroys all of the feeds, apps, and

00:14:58.790 --> 00:15:00.280
labelers running on the protocol.

00:15:00.280 --> 00:15:04.080
So, the pain of destroying the network of open applications needs

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:07.680
to be severe enough that blue sky cannot consider shutting down our

00:15:07.680 --> 00:15:09.280
PDS access.

00:15:09.280 --> 00:15:12.640
A smaller version of this attack would be blue sky may stop

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:15.240
serving data to particular competitors.

00:15:15.280 --> 00:15:19.530
So, if one big competitor emerges in the ecosystem, maybe

00:15:19.530 --> 00:15:21.680
we keep sharing data to all of the feeds and labelers

00:15:21.750 --> 00:15:25.060
out there, but we cut off access to that one larger

00:15:25.060 --> 00:15:26.280
competitor.

00:15:26.280 --> 00:15:29.180
The things that we need to prevent this are a thriving network

00:15:29.180 --> 00:15:30.250
built on open data.

00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:33.350
If people are relying on open data, then we're incentiv

00:15:33.350 --> 00:15:35.270
ized to not cut off access to it.

00:15:35.280 --> 00:15:39.090
And then, specifically on this cutting off access to particular competitors

00:15:39.090 --> 00:15:41.980
, all of the data is signed and rebroadcastable

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:42.020
.

00:15:42.280 --> 00:15:44.110
That means that you can get it from any source.

00:15:44.280 --> 00:15:45.840
You can get it from the blue sky PDS, or

00:15:45.880 --> 00:15:47.280
you can get it from another PDS.

00:15:47.280 --> 00:15:54.020
So, we need multiple sources to get data from.

00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:58.010
The next sort of threat is blue sky stops crawling non-

00:15:58.010 --> 00:15:59.270
blue sky PDSs.

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:01.570
So, these are folks that have migrated their account off of

00:16:01.600 --> 00:16:03.740
the blue sky PDS, and the blue sky app view

00:16:03.870 --> 00:16:06.270
stops indexing non-blue sky PDS data.

00:16:06.280 --> 00:16:10.270
Their motivation to do that would be to monopolize hosting.

00:16:10.280 --> 00:16:15.270
What we need to prevent this is a critical mass of users

00:16:15.290 --> 00:16:17.420
on non-blue sky PDSs, and other applications

00:16:17.420 --> 00:16:19.280
that do index non-blue sky PDS data.

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:23.340
And that, I want to call out that critical mass,

00:16:23.340 --> 00:16:25.770
basically we need the critical mass, because if blue sky were

00:16:25.880 --> 00:16:28.510
to stop indexing this, you needed to screw up people

00:16:28.510 --> 00:16:30.760
's experience of the app, and they would get pissed because

00:16:30.870 --> 00:16:32.970
there's data that they want to see that they're not

00:16:32.970 --> 00:16:34.270
seeing in the blue sky app.

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:36.530
I want to call out that I don't think that we

00:16:36.530 --> 00:16:42.560
need like an even distribution of users across hosting infrastructure in the

00:16:42.560 --> 00:16:44.280
network in order to achieve this.

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:47.680
You can imagine 5% of the network, even less than

00:16:47.680 --> 00:16:48.270
that.

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:50.420
If it's an important 5% of the network, that

00:16:50.420 --> 00:16:53.270
would be disruptive enough that if you cut off access to them

00:16:53.280 --> 00:16:56.280
, people would be upset and leave the blue sky app.

00:16:56.280 --> 00:17:00.420
This threat also becomes much less substantial if people can just go

00:17:00.420 --> 00:17:03.280
to another app that is indexing both blue sky content,

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:06.280
and content from non-blue sky PDSs.

00:17:06.280 --> 00:17:12.240
So having other applications in the network helps prevent this threat.

00:17:12.280 --> 00:17:15.280
Another threat is blue sky messing with accounts.

00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:19.000
Examples of this are preventing users from migrating between PDS

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:21.990
s, de-platforming users, especially if we don

00:17:21.990 --> 00:17:25.420
't have Just Cause, preventing users from using certain apps or

00:17:25.420 --> 00:17:26.280
competitors.

00:17:26.280 --> 00:17:30.950
The things that we need to prevent this are basically account recovery

00:17:30.950 --> 00:17:32.240
or export tools.

00:17:32.280 --> 00:17:35.710
So backups of repositories if blue sky is refusing to serve

00:17:35.710 --> 00:17:37.270
your repository to you.

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:41.280
User held recovery keys in case blue sky is refusing to sign

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:43.280
account migration operations on your behalf.

00:17:43.280 --> 00:17:45.070
And then just a place to go.

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:48.650
Non-blue sky PDS is running in the network that

00:17:48.650 --> 00:17:50.270
you can migrate to.

00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:54.200
And then the final threat is blue sky just losing access to

00:17:54.220 --> 00:17:55.270
accounts.

00:17:55.280 --> 00:17:59.320
This may be sort of out of ill intentions or this may

00:17:59.320 --> 00:18:01.240
be external forces.

00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:03.890
So going out of business, you know, a data center

00:18:03.890 --> 00:18:07.860
blowing up, legal action, servers getting seized, something like

00:18:07.860 --> 00:18:08.280
that.

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:10.100
I would expect in most cases blue sky should be able to

00:18:10.310 --> 00:18:11.280
help ease this transition.

00:18:11.280 --> 00:18:14.030
For instance, like the most likely one of these is probably

00:18:14.030 --> 00:18:15.280
blue sky going out of business.

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:18.500
And we should be able to help ease the transition if that

00:18:18.500 --> 00:18:19.280
were the case.

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:21.870
Even if we stop providing PDS services, it's very

00:18:21.870 --> 00:18:24.920
cheap for us to keep some PDS's online and rotation

00:18:24.920 --> 00:18:26.280
keys as people move off.

00:18:26.280 --> 00:18:29.420
In extreme cases where blue sky is refusing to do that or

00:18:29.420 --> 00:18:32.710
unable to do it for some reason, we essentially need what

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:35.920
we got from the last threat, which is backups of reposit

00:18:35.920 --> 00:18:38.020
ories and user held recovery keys.

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:43.450
So pulling out the things that we found that we needed for

00:18:43.450 --> 00:18:46.770
each of these, it's basically app view implementation and sync

00:18:46.770 --> 00:18:47.280
tooling.

00:18:47.280 --> 00:18:51.280
Nice.

00:18:51.280 --> 00:18:53.440
More users on non-blue sky PDS's, so

00:18:53.440 --> 00:18:56.270
a more diverse open data hosting layer.

00:18:56.280 --> 00:19:01.100
Consumer key management and recovery tools, putting rotation keys in the

00:19:01.130 --> 00:19:02.240
hands of users.

00:19:02.280 --> 00:19:05.280
Other data sources and backups for repositories.

00:19:05.280 --> 00:19:08.280
And then a thriving ecosystem built on open data.

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:10.570
So I want to walk through each one of these and talk

00:19:10.580 --> 00:19:12.280
about what the blue sky team can do, what we are

00:19:12.280 --> 00:19:14.500
doing, and then what folks in the ecosystem can do if

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:17.270
you're concerned about these particular threats.

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:25.580
So, first on app view implementation and sync

00:19:25.580 --> 00:19:26.280
.

00:19:26.280 --> 00:19:27.280
Relays are cheap now.

00:19:27.280 --> 00:19:28.080
With sync 1.

00:19:28.080 --> 00:19:30.780
1, FIG is running a relay for under $5

00:19:30.780 --> 00:19:31.200
a month.

00:19:31.280 --> 00:19:32.280
That's awesome.

00:19:32.280 --> 00:19:34.100
There's over 10 full network relays running in the network

00:19:34.100 --> 00:19:34.100
.

00:19:34.280 --> 00:19:37.280
We seem to be getting pretty good at doing this one.

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:40.040
So you can get your data from a lot of different sources

00:19:40.040 --> 00:19:40.280
.

00:19:40.280 --> 00:19:42.100
There's lots of new sync tools coming out.

00:19:42.280 --> 00:19:47.220
We published tap, hydrant, the entire FIG proto

00:19:47.220 --> 00:19:50.280
microcosm universe is helping with sync.

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:54.070
And then black sky is actually running a full network app view

00:19:54.070 --> 00:19:55.270
, which is incredible.

00:19:55.280 --> 00:20:02.590
So in some sense, I kind of think this one's

00:20:02.590 --> 00:20:05.280
solved, although we can always do better on it.

00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:08.090
But there's also novel approaches like red dwarf that provide a

00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:10.280
blue sky like experience with no app view.

00:20:10.280 --> 00:20:13.670
And so there's ways to rethink what this looks like in

00:20:13.670 --> 00:20:16.380
the network where maybe, I think it's amazing that black

00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:17.280
sky is running a full network app view.

00:20:17.280 --> 00:20:20.900
I think that you can probably provide blue sky like experiences for

00:20:20.900 --> 00:20:24.720
significantly cheaper if you make certain trade offs in how you construct

00:20:25.130 --> 00:20:25.280
this.

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:29.840
The next one, Cuba joked that we should take a

00:20:29.840 --> 00:20:35.280
shot every time this graph is showed at the conference.

00:20:35.280 --> 00:20:38.280
And I told him I got one more for him.

00:20:38.280 --> 00:20:40.920
The next one is more users on non blue sky PDS

00:20:40.920 --> 00:20:41.280
s.

00:20:41.280 --> 00:20:44.700
This is a graph of weekly users posting from non blue sky

00:20:44.700 --> 00:20:45.270
PDSs.

00:20:45.280 --> 00:20:47.070
And you can see that the trend line is pretty good.

00:20:47.280 --> 00:20:49.490
So in some sense, we just got to keep cooking on

00:20:49.490 --> 00:20:51.270
this and doing what we're doing.

00:20:51.280 --> 00:20:52.960
What blue sky, what we can do and what we're

00:20:52.960 --> 00:20:56.440
planning to do to help with this is putting an account migration

00:20:56.440 --> 00:20:57.280
UI in the PDS.

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:00.870
We think that users, especially non technical users, probably just

00:21:00.870 --> 00:21:04.280
have a better trust relationship with the blue sky PDS.

00:21:04.280 --> 00:21:07.180
Or yeah, with the blue sky PDS and would trust

00:21:07.180 --> 00:21:11.060
an account migration UI there a little bit more to get over

00:21:11.060 --> 00:21:13.280
to non blue sky PDS hosting.

00:21:13.280 --> 00:21:16.140
We want to improve the PDS distribution, especially for mid

00:21:16.140 --> 00:21:18.630
-sized deployments, things in the 1,000 to

00:21:18.630 --> 00:21:20.280
100,000 user range.

00:21:20.280 --> 00:21:22.110
Right now it works pretty well for self-hosters and

00:21:22.310 --> 00:21:23.280
small groups of people.

00:21:23.280 --> 00:21:25.460
It's a little bit of a pain for mid-sized

00:21:25.460 --> 00:21:26.280
deployments.

00:21:26.280 --> 00:21:28.750
And we also want to make the relay more self-s

00:21:28.750 --> 00:21:32.690
erve, both for third party relays, so that it

00:21:32.690 --> 00:21:35.790
's easier for them to get proactive write notifications whenever PDS

00:21:35.790 --> 00:21:37.270
is right.

00:21:37.280 --> 00:21:39.950
But also for our relay doing dynamic rate limits so that you

00:21:39.950 --> 00:21:43.240
guys don't have to DM us whenever you run into that

00:21:43.290 --> 00:21:46.280
and you get cut off from the relay.

00:21:46.280 --> 00:21:49.660
What you all can do for this to improve this is keep

00:21:49.660 --> 00:21:53.280
cooking and also backup and recovery systems.

00:21:53.280 --> 00:21:57.260
We talked about backup and recovery systems in the context of sort

00:21:57.260 --> 00:22:01.280
of blue sky threatening people's repositories and keys.

00:22:01.280 --> 00:22:04.630
But it's also important for migrating off to non blue

00:22:04.630 --> 00:22:08.600
sky PDS's because you don't necessarily, you know

00:22:08.600 --> 00:22:10.280
, you're taking on an operational risk whenever you do that

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:10.280
.

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:13.970
You kind of know blue sky has money and you know how

00:22:13.970 --> 00:22:16.820
we operate stuff and you know that we're probably keeping your

00:22:16.830 --> 00:22:17.280
data secure.

00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:19.900
Whenever you move to another PDS or even self-host

00:22:19.900 --> 00:22:23.360
ing, you take on some operational risk and having backup and

00:22:23.360 --> 00:22:26.280
recovery systems can give you peace of mind to do that.

00:22:26.280 --> 00:22:32.560
The next thing that we call that was other data sources and

00:22:32.730 --> 00:22:34.280
backups for repositories.

00:22:34.280 --> 00:22:37.820
Phil, Fig, bad example, just announced Hubble, which

00:22:37.820 --> 00:22:40.240
is funded via a grant from blue sky.

00:22:40.280 --> 00:22:42.100
I'm super stoked about this project.

00:22:42.310 --> 00:22:44.280
Hubble's a full network mirror of public repositories.

00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:47.800
The relay used to offer this whenever we switched to sync 1

00:22:47.800 --> 00:22:48.010
.

00:22:48.010 --> 00:22:48.280
1.

00:22:48.280 --> 00:22:51.280
It no longer mirrors all the public repositories in the network

00:22:51.280 --> 00:22:51.280
.

00:22:51.280 --> 00:22:55.720
And so this provides a full network copy of all of the

00:22:55.720 --> 00:22:56.270
data.

00:22:56.280 --> 00:22:58.110
It's intended to increase network resilience.

00:22:58.280 --> 00:23:00.070
This is a backup of your repository.

00:23:00.280 --> 00:23:03.120
If your PDS crashes and burns and you lose your repository

00:23:03.120 --> 00:23:04.280
, you can go get it from here.

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:06.420
If blue sky tries to lock you out of it, you

00:23:06.420 --> 00:23:08.200
can go get a backup of your repository here.

00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:11.010
Or if blue sky shuts down our APIs, then you can

00:23:11.010 --> 00:23:13.270
go sync repositories from Hubble.

00:23:13.280 --> 00:23:15.570
All of the code will be open source and permissibly

00:23:15.590 --> 00:23:16.280
licensed.

00:23:16.280 --> 00:23:18.740
Phil's planning on running an instance of this, but anybody

00:23:18.790 --> 00:23:22.020
can run an instance of this and provide a full network mirror

00:23:22.120 --> 00:23:22.240
.

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:26.280
Consumer key management and recovery tools.

00:23:26.280 --> 00:23:29.080
I actually think that there's a really great product opportunity here

00:23:29.080 --> 00:23:29.280
.

00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:31.100
And I'm kind of surprised that nobody's done it.

00:23:31.280 --> 00:23:34.640
You can take advantage of phone TPMs for storing recovery

00:23:34.640 --> 00:23:36.270
keys in a very secure way.

00:23:36.280 --> 00:23:39.610
This application could also audit PLC and notify users of any

00:23:39.610 --> 00:23:41.270
unexpected operations.

00:23:41.280 --> 00:23:44.120
And just to note, I also think that this would partner

00:23:44.120 --> 00:23:46.280
well with a backup or recovery service.

00:23:46.280 --> 00:23:49.280
Especially whenever we put out permission data.

00:23:49.280 --> 00:23:52.500
And then the final thing is just a thriving ecosystem built on

00:23:52.500 --> 00:23:53.270
open data.

00:23:53.280 --> 00:23:55.530
And this is, I think, the biggest part where you

00:23:55.530 --> 00:23:56.280
all come in.

00:23:56.280 --> 00:23:59.820
Apps built on the atmosphere, atmospheric websites, feeds, label

00:23:59.820 --> 00:24:01.270
ers, social media tools.

00:24:01.280 --> 00:24:03.110
Anything that requires that the data be open.

00:24:03.280 --> 00:24:06.650
In some sense, all of the previous threats that we talked

00:24:06.650 --> 00:24:09.280
about are, they're pretty protocol brained.

00:24:09.280 --> 00:24:10.980
And I just don't think a lot of users are going

00:24:10.980 --> 00:24:12.280
to care or engage about that.

00:24:12.280 --> 00:24:14.410
And I don't think that we're going to get to

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:18.380
like an even distribution of users by focusing on key recovery or

00:24:18.400 --> 00:24:20.280
non blue sky PDS's or anything like that.

00:24:20.280 --> 00:24:23.710
The most important thing for the resilience of the network is that

00:24:23.710 --> 00:24:26.560
users need to understand that they're participating in a multi-

00:24:26.560 --> 00:24:27.280
stakeholder network.

00:24:27.280 --> 00:24:29.110
That they're participating in the atmosphere.

00:24:29.280 --> 00:24:31.100
That they're not participating in blue sky.

00:24:31.280 --> 00:24:34.090
And so if we're building things that run on open data

00:24:34.090 --> 00:24:37.240
and users fall in love with open social.

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:40.280
And these experiences that you can only build on open data.

00:24:40.280 --> 00:24:42.460
That is the most important thing that we can do to keep

00:24:42.460 --> 00:24:43.280
blue sky honest.

00:24:43.280 --> 00:24:46.280
And to keep the open social web running.

00:24:46.280 --> 00:24:49.610
So the best way to ensure the resilience of the network is

00:24:49.610 --> 00:24:53.020
to build something that people love so much that they would revolt

00:24:53.290 --> 00:24:54.280
if it ever went away.

00:24:54.280 --> 00:24:56.110
Sweet.

00:24:56.280 --> 00:24:57.280
Thank you.

